The Architectural Epistemology of Ibadi Islam: Textual Transmission, Cosmological Narratives, and the Geopolitics of Strict TawhidIntroduction to the Ibadi Scholarly Paradigm and Historiographical VulnerabilityThe historical and theological trajectory of Ibadi Islam represents one of the most intricate, resilient, and continuously marginalized traditions within the broader Islamic intellectual corpus. Far from being a mere peripheral offshoot of early Islamic political schisms, the Ibadi tradition has cultivated a profound, self-sustaining epistemological framework that intertwines strict theological rationalism with a deeply embedded political philosophy of resistance. At the core of this tradition lies an uncompromising, almost fiercely guarded commitment to absolute monotheism (Tawhid), a rigorous and systematic rejection of anthropomorphism (Tashbih), and a distinct cosmological narrative preserved through highly specialized, geographically isolated channels of textual transmission.An exhaustive analysis of the surviving internal Ibadi scholarly corpus reveals a systemic, repeating pattern throughout the first three centuries of Islamic history: the development and preservation of theological doctrine cannot be decoupled from the immense geopolitical pressures exerted by the surrounding Umayyad and Abbasid empires. The systematic destruction of independent Ibadi states, the catastrophic loss of foundational texts such as the Diwan of Jabir ibn Zayd, and the forced geographic isolation of Ibadi communities in the remote mountains of Oman and the Maghreb have fundamentally shaped the survival, structure, and hermeneutics of their textual tradition.The institutional apparatus of the early Islamic empires did not merely seek military dominance; it actively sought theological hegemony. The promotion of doctrines that allowed for a physically conceptualized deity—often drawing upon narratives from the People of the Book (Ahl al-Kitab)—served the ideological needs of dynastic rulers who positioned themselves as the physical shadows of God on earth. In direct opposition to this, the Ibadi scholars maintained a doctrine of radical divine transcendence. This report provides an exhaustive, in-depth synthesis of the Ibadi conceptualization of creation, cosmology, prophetic epistemology, and divine attributes, utilizing surviving fragments, foundational Hadith collections like the Musnad of al-Rabi' bin Habib, and the extensive exegetical works of later scholars such as Muhammad bin Yusuf Atfiyyash (specifically Himyan al-Zad and Taysir al-Tafsir). By rigorously examining the intersections of scriptural interpretation, manuscript transmission, and political survival, a highly nuanced understanding of Ibadi theological ontology emerges, revealing how divergence in the Hadith corpus serves as critical historical data regarding institutional suppression.The Epistemological Fracture: Jabir ibn Zayd and the Tragedy of the Lost DiwanTo fully comprehend the depth of Ibadi cosmology and creation narratives, one must first reckon with the severe historiographical gaps caused by the deliberate destruction of foundational manuscripts. The foremost intellectual architect and spiritual progenitor of the Ibadi movement was Jabir ibn Zayd, a prominent scholar of the Tabi'un generation residing in Basra. Jabir was highly esteemed by the Prophet’s companion 'Abd Allah ibn Abbas, who reportedly considered him the most knowledgeable interpreter of the Qur'an, stating that if the people of Basra strictly followed Jabir's rulings, it would expansively encompass them in knowledge of the Book of God.Jabir ibn Zayd was not a peripheral figure; he was deeply embedded in the administrative machinery of the early Islamic state, working within the Diwan (administrative registry) in Basra and maintaining close, albeit highly fraught, ties with the scribes of the tyrannical Umayyad governor Al-Hajjaj bin Yusuf. Despite his proximity to power, Jabir remained fiercely critical of Umayyad oppression, maintaining a clandestine network of scholars and political dissidents. It is from this matrix of immense scholarly authority and covert political resistance that Jabir compiled his magnum opus: a massive, seven-volume compendium of Hadith, jurisprudence, and exegesis known simply as the Diwan.The Weaponization of Textual Control and Factional SabotageThe fate of Jabir ibn Zayd's Diwan perfectly and tragically illustrates the extreme vulnerability of non-state intellectual traditions. According to historical records preserved in Ibadi encyclopedias and biographical dictionaries, a complete manuscript of the seven-volume Diwan was housed almost exclusively within royal or highly restricted libraries, effectively locked away from the public and the broader scholarly community. There are historical indications that a manuscript of this monumental work existed in the royal library of the Abbasid Caliph Harun al-Rashid (reigned 170-193 AH / 786-809 CE), demonstrating that the imperial center recognized its value, even if they suppressed its widespread dissemination.However, the primary tragedy resulting in the complete eradication of the text occurred within the context of internal Ibadi political factionalism in the Maghreb. During the era of the Rustamid Imamate in North Africa, a prominent religious scholar, political dissident, and founder of the Naffathiyya sub-sect, Naffath (Faraj) bin Nasr al-Nafusi, sought access to the text. Naffath was a staunch, vitriolic opponent of the reigning Rustamid Imam Aflah bin Abd al-Wahhab. He condemned the Imam for what he perceived as a lack of military aggression against the ascendant Abbasid proxy forces (the Aghlabids) and severely criticized the Imam's lifestyle, denouncing his fine clothing and hunting excursions as incompatible with the ascetic ideals of the Imamate.Despite this profound political enmity, Naffath leveraged a rare moment of royal audience to request permission from the Sultan to copy the Diwan of Jabir ibn Zayd. The Sultan, momentarily disregarding the frantic advice of his ministers who warned against releasing such a rare, vital, and politically sensitive manuscript to a known agitator, granted the request. Naffath succeeded in copying the text in its entirety and transported it to his stronghold in the Jabal Nafusa region.What followed is one of the most devastating acts of intellectual sabotage in Islamic history. Driven by extreme factionalism and a theological arrogance that dictated only his specific interpretations were valid, Naffath intentionally burned and destroyed the manuscript of the Diwan. His explicit motivation was to ensure that his political and theological rivals—the mainstream Wahbi Ibadis who supported the Rustamid state—could never access its foundational knowledge to refute his positions or legitimize their governance. This act meant that the primary seven-volume corpus of Jabir ibn Zayd disappeared from human history. Only isolated fragments, theoretical echoes, and specific rulings survived, salvaged largely through the heroic efforts of a scholar named 'Amrus, whose actions are highly praised in Ibadi historiography for saving what little remained from the flames of Naffath's sectarian hatred.The destruction of the Diwan underscores a critical historiographical principle that must be applied to any study of Ibadi theology: the surviving Ibadi corpus is essentially a curated, fractured remnant. Had the Diwan survived, it would have offered unprecedented, systemic insights into the earliest, pre-institutional formulations of Islamic cosmology, prophetic narratives, and the specific hermeneutics applied by the direct, unmediated students of the Prophet's companions.The Transmission of Resistance: Musnad al-Rabi' bin Habib and the Anthropomorphism CrisisWith the catastrophic loss of the Diwan, the Musnad of al-Rabi' bin Habib emerged as the definitive, foundational early Hadith compilation for the Ibadi tradition. Known colloquially among Ibadis as Al-Jami' al-Sahih (The Authentic Collection), it functions as the central pillar of their prophetic epistemology, bridging the gap between the era of the Companions and the later theological systematization of the Ibadi school.Institutional Polemics Against the Ibadi ChainBecause the Musnad relies on an entirely different chain of transmission than the six canonical Sunni books (the Sihah al-Sittah compiled by scholars like Bukhari and Muslim), it has been the subject of relentless, often vitriolic polemical attacks from mainstream Sunni institutional scholars. Where the Sunni chains converge with the Ibadi chains, there is mutual recognition of authenticity; however, where they diverge, the Sunni institutional apparatus has historically labeled the Ibadi transmissions as anomalous or fabricated.Contemporary Salafi/Sunni Hadith scholars, most notably Nasir al-Din al-Albani, have aggressively dismissed the text. In works like the Silsilat al-Ahadith al-Da'ifah (Series of Weak Hadiths), Albani characterizes the Musnad as being "filled with rejected (munkarah) and false (batilah) hadiths," arguing that it contains thousands of reports that contradict the established Sunni orthodox consensus. Other Sunni authors, such as Khalid Abd al-Rahman al-Misri in his highly critical work Tahdhir al-Muslimin min Musnad al-Rabi' bin Habib (Warning Muslims against the Musnad of al-Rabi'), have systematically attempted to discredit the compilation on methodological and theological grounds.Critics frequently highlight supposed logical or theological contradictions to invalidate the text. For instance, Sunni polemicists point to a Hadith in the Musnad stating that a martyr killed in battle should not be washed, for on the Day of Judgment, his blood will return smelling of musk. Critics argue this is a "mistake" because it contradicts the Qur'anic promise (e.g., Surah Al-Qiyama 75:4) that God will resurrect humans perfectly intact, right down to their fingertips, meaning the presence of bleeding wounds on the Day of Judgment represents a physical contradiction. However, these criticisms frequently stem from a fundamental misunderstanding of, or a refusal to engage with, the Ibadi hermeneutical approach, which heavily favors metaphorical and spiritual interpretations over crude literalistic readings when describing eschatological realities or divine interactions.The Centrality of Tawhid and the Rejection of TashbihThe true source of friction between the Musnad and the Sunni institutional consensus lies not in minor issues of ritual purity, but in the explosive domain of Tawhid (monotheism) and the nature of the Divine. The Musnad provides critical insights into the early Ibadi understanding of creation, the structure of the cosmos, and the rigorous defense against anthropomorphism (Tashbih).A pivotal section of the Musnad is devoted to the interpretation of the divine "establishment" on the Throne (Istiwa 'ala al-'Arsh). The text explicitly and forcefully rejects any spatial, physical, or directional containment of the Divine essence. The Musnad relates a powerful encounter involving the companion Abd Allah ibn Mas'ud. According to the text, Ibn Mas'ud passed by a man who was teaching narratives derived from the Torah (Isra'iliyyat). The man claimed that when God created the heavens and the earth, He physically ascended to the sky from the city of Jerusalem and placed His foot upon the rock of the Temple Mount.Horrified by this blatant spatial anthropomorphism, Ibn Mas'ud immediately invoked the Qur'anic narrative of the Prophet Abraham. Abraham rejected the worship of celestial bodies precisely because they experience movement, transition, and setting ("I like not those that disappear" - Qur'an 6:76), arguing that assigning a physical location, movement, or transition to the Creator equates to polytheism. Ibn Mas'ud warned his companions that a time would inevitably come when people would pray, fast, and perform the Hajj, yet they would be internal disbelievers. He diagnosed this hidden disbelief as stemming from their conceptualization of God with physical boundaries (hudud) and spatial transitions (zawal).Regarding the specific theological challenge of the verse "The Most Merciful established Himself above the Throne" (Qur'an 20:5) , the Musnad records the interpretation of Ibn Mas'ud and the early exegete Al-Dahhak bin Muzahim. They asserted that Istiwa means that God established total dominance, sovereignty, and control over the Throne and all created things, such that all of creation submitted and yielded to Him. The text draws upon classical Arabic linguistics, noting that Arabs frequently use the phrase "a man established (istawa) himself over the wealth of another," meaning he took comprehensive, unassailable control of it, not that he literally, physically sat upon the coins.Thus, in early Ibadi cosmology, the Throne (Al-'Arsh) is understood not as a physical chair or a localized resting place for the Creator, but as the metaphysical apex of the created order, over which God exercises absolute, simultaneous governance without being contained by it. The Musnad presents a devastatingly simple logical argument against the anthropomorphists: If it is acceptable for Sunni theologians to interpret the verse "He is with you wherever you are" (Qur'an 57:4) metaphorically—arguing that God is present through His knowledge and power rather than His physical essence occupying the same room as a human—then it is equally necessary and intellectually consistent to interpret His establishment on the Throne as the establishment of His command and knowledge, rather than a physical posture. To permit metaphor in one verse but enforce literalism in another is exposed as an arbitrary ideological choice, not a coherent theological system.Ibn Abbas’s Prophecy and the Ideological Weaponization of TashbihThe most striking and structurally significant piece of data within the Ibadi transmission chain is a direct, chilling prophecy attributed to 'Abd Allah ibn Abbas regarding the ultimate corruption of Islamic theology. While mainstream Sunni traditions celebrate Ibn Abbas as the "Interpreter of the Qur'an," the Ibadi corpus preserves warnings from him that explicitly indict the later theological developments of the Umayyad and Abbasid state-sponsored clerics.According to the Ibadi tradition, Ibn Abbas warned that the Muslim community would eventually become completely oblivious to true Tawhid. He predicted the rise of an ideological faction that would subvert the transcendence of God. The specific Arabic terminology used in this warning is vital: Ibn Abbas stated that there would arise "a people who describe their Lord with human attributes (yasiifuna rabbahum bi-l-bashar), and they will name those who oppose them 'disbelievers' (kafirin), and they are the ones who are truly deserving of that title; they are the oppressors (zalimun)".The prophecy further outlines the exact methodology this anthropomorphic faction would use: they would differ after clear proofs had come to them, and they would rely heavily on ambiguous verses (mutashabihat), superficial theological doubts (shubuhat), and narratives derived from the People of the Book (riwayat ahl al-kitab) to construct a localized, physical deity.This warning, vehemently preserved and continuously cited within the Ibadi corpus, serves as a direct indictment of the anthropomorphism problem that plagued early Islamic theology. For Ibadi scholars, the divergence in textual transmission regarding this specific warning is highly indicative of institutional suppression. Where the Ibadi and Sunni chains diverge on matters of divine attributes, the divergence itself functions as historical data. The Ibadi perspective maintains that traditions warning against Tashbih were systematically suppressed or allowed to fade by the institutional apparatuses of the Umayyad and Abbasid courts, while traditions supporting a physical, localized deity (often mirroring the Byzantine or Persian concepts of a divine king sitting on a physical throne) were elevated to serve the ideological needs of the Caliphs.The Theological Rejection of the Beatific Vision (Ru'yat Allah)The strict adherence to divine transcendence naturally and necessarily extends into Ibadi eschatology, particularly regarding the highly contentious issue of the "Vision of God" (Ru'yat Allah). While orthodox Sunni theology (including the Ash'ari, Maturidi, and Hanbali/Athari schools) universally affirms that believers will physically see God in the afterlife, Ibadi doctrine categorically rejects this possibility, classifying it as a supreme manifestation of Tashbih.Ibadi theologians argue from first principles of physics and optics: the act of seeing inherently requires physical dimensions, a specific distance, the reflection of light, a focal point, and boundaries. To suggest that God can be seen by human eyes—even transformed heavenly eyes—is to subjugate the Divine to the limitations of His own physical creation. They substantiate this absolute negation with the definitive Qur'anic verse: "Vision perceives Him not, but He perceives [all] vision; and He is the Subtle, the Acquainted" (Qur'an 6:103).When confronted with Hadith traditions suggesting that believers will see God "as you see the full moon," Ibadi scholars dismiss them on methodological grounds. They argue that these reports are solitary transmissions (Ahad), which yield only probabilistic knowledge (Zann). Probabilistic knowledge is insufficient to establish foundational creedal beliefs (Aqa'id), especially when such reports directly contradict the definitive, universally transmitted (Mutawatir) text of the Qur'an. Furthermore, verses utilized by Sunnis to prove the beatific vision, such as "Some faces, that Day, will be radiant, looking at their Lord" (Qur'an 75:22-23), are interpreted metaphorically by Ibadi exegetes. They apply classical Arabic linguistic principles to demonstrate that "looking at" (ila rabbihah nazirah) in this context means "waiting for the reward of their Lord," a usage common in pre-Islamic poetry.The following table synthesizes the fundamental epistemological and doctrinal divergences between the Ibadi tradition and the mainstream Sunni consensus regarding divine attributes and eschatology:Theological ConceptSunni Consensus (Ash'ari / Maturidi / Athari)Ibadi Doctrinal PositionEpistemological / Hermeneutical RationaleDivine Attributes (Hands, Face, Descent)Affirmed as real. Ash'aris interpret metaphorically; Atharis accept literally without modality (bi-la kayf).Strictly and exclusively metaphorical. Literalism is a path to Tashbih (anthropomorphism).Absolute monotheism (Tawhid) strictly forbids assigning physical limits, limbs, or spatial movement to the Creator.Vision of God (Ru'yat Allah)Strongly affirmed for believers in the afterlife as the ultimate reward.Categorically rejected in both this world and the hereafter.Vision requires physical dimensions, distance, and light. God cannot be subjected to created laws of optics.Status of the Grave Sinner (Kaba'ir)Remains a believer; subject to God's mercy. Will eventually enter Heaven after temporary punishment.Commits "Kufr Ni'mah" (ingratitude/hypocrisy). Faces eternal damnation in Hell if unrepentant.Divine justice requires permanent consequences for unrepented major sins; the Qur'an states Heaven is pure, and sinners cannot enter.The Nature of the Qur'anUncreated and eternal (co-eternal with God's essence).Created by God.If the Qur'an is eternal, it compromises Tawhid by positing an eternal entity alongside God. Only God is eternal.Atfiyyash’s Cosmology: The Architecture of the Heavens and the Infinitude of the DivineTo fully reconstruct the internal Ibadi scholarly discourse on creation and cosmology, one must venture beyond early Hadith collections and examine the extended exegetical (Tafsir) tradition. This tradition reached its absolute zenith in the monumental works of Muhammad bin Yusuf Atfiyyash (d. 1332 AH / 1914 CE), a scholar universally revered within the Ibadi tradition as Qutb al-A'imma (The Pole of the Imams). His exhaustive, multi-volume exegesis, Himyan al-Zad ila Dar al-Ma'ad, and its slightly more accessible abridgment, Taysir al-Tafsir, represent the most comprehensive harmonization of Ibadi theology, jurisprudence, and cosmology ever produced.The Mathematical Ratio of CreationAtfiyyash's Himyan al-Zad provides a staggeringly detailed, awe-inspiring structural map of creation. The cosmology presented in his exegesis is specifically designed to emphasize the overwhelming, incomprehensible majesty of God and the comparative microscopic insignificance of humanity. The architecture of the cosmos is built upon a mathematical ratio of existence that exponentially stretches the boundaries of human imagination.According to the deep cosmological traditions recorded by Atfiyyash, the demographic distribution of conscious, living, and created beings operates on an exponential scale of ten, layering reality from the terrestrial to the highest celestial realms:Humanity vs. Jinn: The entire population of humanity (the descendants of Adam, from the first man to the Day of Judgment) constitutes merely one-tenth of the total population of the Jinn.Jinn vs. Terrestrial Fauna: The combined population of humans and Jinn together constitutes merely one-tenth of the animals that roam the land.Land vs. Air: The animals of the land are merely one-tenth of the birds of the air.Air vs. Sea: The birds are merely one-tenth of the creatures that inhabit the oceans and seas.Terrestrial vs. Angelic (Earth): The staggering multitude of sea creatures constitutes merely one-tenth of the angels specifically assigned to the Earth.Earth vs. First Heaven: The angels of the Earth are merely one-tenth of the angels inhabiting the First Heaven (the lowest celestial sphere).This exponential multiplication continues relentlessly upwards through the seven heavens; the inhabitants of each heaven are merely ten percent of the heaven above it. Finally, the total, unimaginable sum of all entities within the seven heavens, the earth, the seas, and the spiritual realms amounts to only a fraction of the angelic beings that surround the Divine Throne (Al-'Arsh).Atfiyyash describes the Throne as possessing one hundred thousand canopies or pavilions (suradiq). The sheer scale is paralyzing: the length of just one of these one hundred thousand canopies is equivalent to the combined width of the heavens, the earth, and everything contained within them. In this unfathomable expanse, Atfiyyash notes that there is not a single handspan of space that is not occupied by an angel in a state of eternal prostration, bowing, or standing, generating a continuous, thunderous hum of glorification (Tasbih), declaring the oneness (Tahlil), and sanctifying (Taqdis) God.This cosmological hierarchy serves a profound dual purpose within Ibadi epistemology. Theologically, it entirely annihilates any human-centric arrogance. By placing humanity at the absolute numerical and spatial bottom of the created order, it shatters the ego of the anthropomorphist who seeks to imagine God in a human form. Epistemologically, it serves as the ultimate defensive barrier for Tawhid; if the created Throne is so impossibly, infinitely vast that the human mind cannot even begin to process its dimensions, attempting to ascribe localized human-like physical dimensions, hands, or faces to the Creator of that Throne is exposed as the ultimate theological absurdity and a gross insult to the Divine Majesty.Prophetic Infallibility and the Mechanics of Ijtihad in Ibadi ExegesisBeyond the macro-level structure of the cosmos, Atfiyyash's Taysir al-Tafsir extensively addresses the micro-level epistemology of how divine truth is transmitted to humanity. Specifically, he provides a highly nuanced analysis of the nature of prophetic knowledge and the concept of Ijtihad (independent legal and theological reasoning) as applied to the Prophets themselves.A central question in Islamic theology is whether Prophets deduce rulings through human intellect when revelation is silent, or whether they act solely upon direct, unceasing revelation. Analyzing Atfiyyash's methodology reveals a sophisticated balance between acknowledging the humanity of the Prophet and maintaining the absolute purity of the religion. Atfiyyash posits that the Prophet Muhammad—and indeed all prior prophets—did engage in Ijtihad when direct revelation was temporarily absent.However, Atfiyyash emphasizes that prophetic Ijtihad differs fundamentally from the Ijtihad of ordinary scholars. When a Prophet exercises independent reasoning, he is backed by a divine safeguard that guarantees the ultimate truth of the resulting law. If the Prophet's deduction is correct, God confirms it through subsequent revelation or divine silence, thereby establishing it as a binding religious proof (Hujjah) for all Muslims. Conversely, if the Prophet's reasoning is flawed or suboptimal, God immediately intervenes via revelation to correct the error. Atfiyyash explains that God "informs him of the correct path, so that he abandons the [flawed conclusion]" before it can become permanently established as religious law.This hermeneutical framework perfectly balances the human nature of the Prophets—acknowledging their capacity for independent thought and temporal deduction—with their functional, outcome-based infallibility in transmitting the faith. It provides a robust analytical tool for Ibadi scholars to interpret Qur'anic verses where Prophets appear to be reprimanded or corrected by God (such as the incident of the blind man in Surah 'Abasa, or David's initial judgment in Surah Sad). Rather than viewing these incidents as moral failings or sins, the Ibadi exegetical tradition views them as the divine refinement and calibration of prophetic Ijtihad, ensuring that the final law delivered to the community is flawlessly aligned with the Divine Will.The Geopolitical Annihilation of Ibadi Autonomy: The Umayyad CampaignsThe survival of the highly refined texts detailing these complex cosmological and theological frameworks cannot be understood in a vacuum; they must be contextualized within the brutal geopolitical reality faced by the Ibadi community. The institutional apparatuses of the Umayyad and Abbasid empires correctly recognized that Ibadi theology was not merely an abstract academic exercise confined to the mosque. It was inextricably linked to a revolutionary political philosophy that utterly rejected dynastic succession in favor of a meritocratic, divinely sanctioned Imamate, where the ruler was bound strictly to the Qur'an and could be deposed if he deviated from justice. Consequently, independent Ibadi states that resisted incorporation into the imperial center were targeted for systematic, overwhelming military destruction.The Uprising of Talib al-Haqq and Abu HamzaDuring the twilight years of the Umayyad Caliphate under Marwan II (often referred to derogatorily as Marwan al-Himar), the Ibadi movement launched a massive, highly coordinated uprising originating from the peripheral regions of the Arabian Peninsula. The rebellion was led by the ascetic and charismatic figure Abd Allah bin Yahya al-Kindi, who assumed the messianic title "Talib al-Haqq" (The Seeker of Truth). He was joined by his brilliant military and ideological commander, Abu Hamza (Al-Mukhtar bin 'Awf al-Azdi).Abu Hamza's strategy was highly sophisticated, leveraging the annual Hajj pilgrimage as a platform for ideological dissemination and political theater. In the year 129 AH, Abu Hamza and his highly disciplined followers appeared at Mount Arafat, conspicuously dressed, bearing black banners, and openly challenging the legitimacy of the Umayyad authority before the assembled Muslim world. The Umayyad governor of the Hijaz, Abd al-Wahid bin Sulayman bin Abd al-Malik, found himself militarily unprepared and politically paralyzed. Confronting the highly motivated, zealous Ibadi force during the sacred rites risked a catastrophic bloodbath. Consequently, a tense temporary truce was negotiated, allowing both factions to complete the Hajj independently. The humiliating terms dictated that Abd al-Wahid would evacuate Mecca immediately after the rites, leaving the holy city to the Ibadis.Following the peaceful occupation of Mecca, Abu Hamza dispatched a force under Balj bin Uqba to advance toward Medina. Governor Abd al-Wahid mobilized a massive force of Medinans and Qurayshi elites to intercept the Ibadis. The two armies met at the Battle of Qudayd. Historical sources indicate a stark contrast between the forces: the Medinan army was poorly disciplined, arrogant, heavily reliant on the prestige of their lineage, and unfamiliar with the harsh realities of warfare. In contrast, the Ibadi revolutionaries were battle-hardened and ideologically driven. Before the battle, superstitious omens plagued the Medinans—a spear broke against a tree, shattering their morale. The Ibadi forces launched a devastating surprise attack, utterly destroying the Umayyad army and resulting in the deaths of an estimated 4,000 men, essentially wiping out a generation of the Qurayshi aristocracy. Following this absolute victory, Abu Hamza triumphantly entered Medina, briefly establishing Ibadi governance over the spiritual centers of Islam.The Umayyad response, directed from Damascus, was swift, massive, and merciless. Marwan II recognized the existential threat and dispatched an elite, heavily armed Syrian force of 4,000 cavalry under the command of Abd al-Malik bin Muhammad bin 'Atiyya al-Sa'di. The armies clashed at Wadi al-Qura. The ideological divide was palpable on the battlefield. Before engaging, Abu Hamza's men attempted to initiate a theological debate with the Syrian forces regarding the application of the Qur'an and the handling of orphans' wealth—reflecting the Ibadi insistence on ethical governance even in war. The Umayyad commander scoffed, mocking their piety, stating they would put the Qur'an in a sack and consume the orphans' wealth, before launching a brutal, overwhelming assault. The Ibadi forces were annihilated, and Abu Hamza was killed. Ibn 'Atiyya subsequently marched relentlessly on Yemen, where he defeated and killed Talib al-Haqq, decapitating him and sending his severed head to the Umayyad court in Damascus as a gruesome trophy of institutional victory.The Abbasid Continuation: The Systematic Erasure of the Omani ImamatesThe transition of imperial power from the Umayyads to the Abbasids offered no respite for the Ibadi tradition; in fact, the ideological persecution intensified. As the Abbasids ruthlessly consolidated power under Abu al-Abbas al-Saffah and later Abu Ja'far al-Mansur, the Ibadis of Oman formally declared their independence. Seeing the bloody chaos of the dynastic transition as proof of the failure of the imperial model, they elected Al-Julanda bin Mas'ud as their legitimate, independent Imam in 132 AH (749 CE).Al-Julanda sought to establish a utopian state modeled strictly on the pure governance of Abu Bakr and Umar. He organized his military into highly disciplined, ethically trained units. In a move reflecting the Ibadi fusion of theology and statecraft, he mandated that every unit of ten soldiers be accompanied by a religious scholar to ensure their conduct remained morally irreproachable.Recognizing the immense ideological threat posed by a successful, righteous, and independent Islamic state on their periphery—a state that inherently delegitimized Abbasid claims to universal authority—the Caliph Al-Saffah moved to crush the Omani Imamate. He dispatched his most ruthless and strategically brilliant commander, Khazim bin Khuzayma al-Tamimi. The ensuing conflict was devastating. Khazim deployed brutal, overwhelming military tactics, eventually defeating the Ibadi forces and killing Imam Al-Julanda bin Mas'ud in 134 AH (751 CE), thereby extinguishing the first Omani Imamate in its infancy. To ensure the state could not immediately rise again, Khazim appointed local despots—such as Muhammad bin Za'ida and Rashid bin al-Nadr—to rule Oman, deliberately fostering corruption, injustice, and tribal factionalism to break the spirit of the local population. The trauma of this invasion was profound; historical anecdotes relate tales of Abbasid soldiers suffering from severe, chronic psychological distress (insomnia and PTSD) years later due to the ferocious, almost suicidal bravery of the Omani fighters they encountered at battles like Julfar.Despite this devastating setback, the Ibadi movement in Oman continuously regenerated, fueled by their theological conviction. In 177 AH (793 CE), during the reign of Harun al-Rashid, the Omani Ibadis successfully annihilated an Abbasid invasion force commanded by Isa bin Ja'far at Wadi Hatta (near Sohar), capturing the commander and securing their independence once more. This fierce resilience sparked centuries of cyclical conflict, culminating in the massive, catastrophic invasion directed by the Abbasid Caliph Al-Mu'tadid. Taking advantage of internal Omani discord and factionalism following the controversial deposition of Imam Al-Salt bin Malik, the Abbasid governor of Bahrain, Muhammad bin Nur, invaded Oman. His campaign brought untold destruction upon the region, temporarily shattering the structural cohesion of the Ibadi state and reinforcing the necessity of concealing their most vital theological texts.The following table synthesizes the cyclical pattern of imperial violence directed against the Ibadi intellectual and political centers, which directly necessitated the isolationist, highly guarded, and decentralized transmission of their textual corpus:Era / YearImperial PowerImperial CommanderTarget of CampaignKey Ibadi FiguresGeopolitical & Theological Outcome129-130 AHUmayyad CaliphateAbd al-Malik bin Muhammad bin 'AtiyyaArabian Peninsula (Hijaz / Medina / Yemen)Abu Hamza (killed), Talib al-Haqq (killed)Brief, revolutionary Ibadi control of the holy cities was broken. The movement was forced back to the geographical peripheries.134 AHAbbasid CaliphateKhazim bin Khuzayma al-TamimiOman (First Omani Imamate)Imam Al-Julanda bin Mas'ud (killed)Destruction of the First Imamate. Imposition of corrupt proxy rulers designed to ideologically demoralize the population.177 AHAbbasid CaliphateIsa bin Ja'farOman (Wadi Hatta / Sohar)Omani tribal forces and scholarsDecisive defeat of the Abbasid force; Ibadi autonomy restored, allowing for the continued, albeit isolated, transmission of texts.Late 3rd C. AHAbbasid CaliphateMuhammad bin NurOmanImam Al-Salt bin Malik (deposed prior)Abbasids exploited internal Ibadi factionalism. Massive destruction of infrastructure and temporary dissolution of the Imamate's central authority.These historical traumas explicitly and deeply inform the Ibadi theological framework. The empire that slaughtered their Imams and burned their cities was the exact same imperial apparatus that sponsored the theological schools propagating anthropomorphism and dynastic absolutism. Thus, for the Ibadi scholar transcribing a manuscript in the mountains of Oman or the valleys of the Maghreb, preserving the metaphorical interpretation of the Throne, rejecting the beatific vision, and affirming the absolute transcendence of God was not merely an academic exercise. It was a profound act of intellectual resistance against an imperial Islam that sought to dominate both the physical world and the ontological nature of God.ConclusionThe Ibadi scholarly corpus regarding creation narratives, cosmology, and prophetic epistemology constitutes a highly sophisticated, rigorously rationalist architecture designed to preserve the absolute purity of Tawhid. Through the meticulous—albeit historically fractured and politically sabotaged—transmission of texts like the Musnad of al-Rabi' bin Habib, and the exhaustive, encyclopedic exegetical volumes of Atfiyyash's Himyan al-Zad and Taysir al-Tafsir, the tradition constructed a theological universe where the Divine is utterly beyond spatial confinement. It is a cosmology where humanity occupies but a microscopic fraction of an infinitely vast angelic hierarchy, perfectly insulating the concept of God from the creeping threat of anthropomorphism.This monumental intellectual achievement is rendered all the more remarkable by the brutal historical conditions of its survival. The deliberate destruction of foundational texts, exemplified by Naffath bin Nasr's factional burning of Jabir ibn Zayd's seven-volume Diwan, severely crippled the early textual record. Furthermore, the relentless, overwhelming military campaigns waged by the Umayyad and Abbasid empires against revolutionary figures like Talib al-Haqq, Abu Hamza, and Al-Julanda bin Mas'ud ensured that the Ibadi tradition would remain a marginalized, persecuted entity forced to the edges of the Islamic world.Yet, it is precisely this persecution that forged the tradition's defining characteristic. The Ibadis demonstrated an uncompromising refusal to synthesize their transcendent theology with the anthropomorphic, spatially bound, and dynastic ideologies promoted by the imperial center. The divergence of the Ibadi text—whether in Hadith chains or cosmological mapping—is not an anomaly of Islamic history to be dismissed by mainstream polemicists. It is a vital, surviving counter-narrative, offering critical historical data on how early Islamic thought resisted the hegemonic institutionalization of the Caliphates.
